	<meta property="og:description" content="When it comes to cold soups, I‚Äôm of two minds. Part of me says that cold soup is as close as it gets to perfect summer fare. I mean, it‚Äôs only logical: so many of the season‚Äôs fruits and vegetables take well to cold preparations, and anyway, there‚Äôs something about a hot, steamy day that begs for a cool, quenching soup. But the other part of me can‚Äôt quite get behind it. Sometimes savory flavors don‚Äôt sit right when served cold and pur√©ed: the taste doesn‚Äôt seem to fit the temperature and texture. Cold soups can taste harsh and kind of squeaky in the mouth, but their flavors seem somehow muted too, without the aroma and richness of their warmer&hellip;" />
